    <title>Combined summary - Standardizing automatic pre-negotiation of transaction terms with BIP70? (Emulating Amazon one-click purchase at all merchants)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T16:46:07.542565+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-February/007388.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>BIP70 is a payment protocol for Bitcoin transactions that allows for communication between a user's wallet and a merchant's server to agree on payment details and other functionalities. However, currently, it only initiates at the time of payment, which can make it difficult for users who want next-day delivery or prefer shopping with an arbitrator involved. To address this issue, there could be a BIP70 HTML tag on web shops that automatically triggers a user's wallet as soon as they visit the page, allowing for notifications on acceptable terms and making every web shop feel like Amazon.However, this method has privacy implications and increases exposure to potential wallet exploits, but these problems can be mitigated by asking users if they intend to shop or not at each site before connecting and sending any information, or by limiting what data is sent until the user agrees to send private information. Additionally, implementing BIP70 HTML tags could allow merchants to send relevant information such as third-party certifications to the user's wallet, which can include certification that shows they have been audited and approved by a specific entity for a specific purpose. With a list of predefined types of certifications that the wallet understands and accepts, it could require a certificate to be present to even allow a purchase.During a discussion about Amazon's payment process, the concept of BIP70 was introduced. BIP70 involves communicating the terms of the sale between the buyer and seller before the payment process begins. This includes information such as whether the seller ships to the buyer's country. By using BIP70, a wallet or browser extension can inform the buyer immediately if they are able to shop at a particular webshop or not, saving time for both parties. The implementation of BIP70 benefits buyers by providing them with essential information before they begin filling their cart, ultimately leading to a smoother transaction process.In another discussion, it was suggested that displaying shipping information on e-commerce websites before the user adds any item to the cart could be useful, but concerns were raised about the reliability of IP addresses and the willingness of users to read through all options. One solution proposed was a browser extension that prompts users with a popup slider showing how much information they are willing to share.Mike Hearn also discussed possible extensions to BIP70, questioning whether the wallet was the best place to auto-fill shipping addresses and suggesting using HTML5 data standards instead. Another suggestion involved adding a tag in the HTML form that prompts the Bitcoin wallet about the payment details, potentially through asking a hardware wallet over BLE for this data. The goal is to make Bitcoin transactions simple and secure, using BIP70 extensions for communication between the wallet and merchant, supporting graceful degradation if the browser or wallet don't support it.Overall, implementing BIP70 HTML tags and extensions could greatly enhance the shopping experience for users while still preserving their privacy and security. It ensures the buyer is aware of all the details of the transaction, including the terms of sale, before making any payments. Hence, the use of BIP70 leads to a smoother transaction process for all parties involved.</summary>
